	"description": "Here&#x27;s the short version.\n\nLet&#x27;s take ringing bells in a church as an example. \n\nA permutation is an ordering of the bells. You&#x27;re figuring out the best order to\nring them in.\n\nA combination is the choice of bells. You&#x27;re choosing the bells to ring. If you\nhave too many bells, you&#x27;d first choose them, and then think about ordering\nthem.\n\nThis gives rise to the familiar identity: (n P r) &#x3D; (n C r) * r!\n\nThe way to order r items out of n is to first choose r items out of n, and then\norder the r it",
